    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-05T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-05T08:00:00-05:00" n="392"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d392">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/665: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-05T21:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 5, 1932—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 5—2:33 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1293. Following from American Consul General at Mukden.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“December 3, 11 a.m. A trustworthy informant states that he has learned from
                        a fairly reliable person who claims to have been secretly informed by
                            <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CC4">Chang Ching-hui</persName>’s
                        secretary that Tokyo has instructed <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CC4"
                            >Chang</persName> to carry out a program which will result in <persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_PH1">Pu-yi</persName> being installed at the
                        Mukden Palace if possible about January 1st as Emperor Hsu an Tung of a
                        Manchu-Mongol Empire. The newly organized Manmeng <persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_HC4">Hsieh Hui</persName> will assist in carrying
                        out the plan. The motives behind the alleged plan are reported to be to
                        obtain the strong support of all Mongolians and Monarchists including those
                        in North China and to facilitate a possible extension [of] territory in the
                        future by evoking the sentimental appeal of a movement for the restoration
                        of the Empire. Efforts to verify this information will be continued.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>The Legation is familiar with these rumors and discussed them briefly in its
                    monthly political report for October (see despatch No. 1814, November 15th, <ref
                        target="#pg_21">pages 21</ref> to <ref target="#pg_25">25</ref>).<note
                        n="45" xml:id="d392fn45">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_ECVH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
